messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path
- /printshops/{printShopID}/employees

All HTTP methods acceptable
- false

HEAD
- false

POST
- true

OPTIONS
- false

TRACE
- false

GET
- true

PUT
- true

DELETE
- false

PATCH
- false

Explanation
- There is no class-level @RequestMapping on ManagerController, so the method-level paths are the full paths (no additional prefix).
- The following handler methods explicitly map to the path /printshops/{printShopID}/employees:
  - getEmployees(...) has @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopID}/employees", method = RequestMethod.GET) → GET is accepted.
  - addEmployee(...) has @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopID}/employees", method = RequestMethod.POST) → POST is accepted.
  - editEmployee(...) has @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopID}/employees", method = RequestMethod.PUT) → PUT is accepted.
- There is a DELETE mapping in the same controller, but it is for the different path /printshops/{printShopID}/employees/{employeeID} (method = RequestMethod.DELETE). Because that includes an additional {employeeID} path parameter, it does not apply to /printshops/{printShopID}/employees, so DELETE is not accepted on the exact path in question.
- No handler in the code explicitly declares HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, PATCH, or a RequestMapping without a method attribute that would accept all methods. Per the instruction to rely on the code (not on runtime framework behavior), those methods are marked as not acceptable.
